# Vercel Web Analytics Integration

## Summary
Successfully integrated Vercel Web Analytics into the HubSportWeb frontend application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Added @vercel/analytics Package
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` package using npm
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with dependency tree

### 2. Integrated Analytics Component
**Modified:** `src/App.jsx`
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/react";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the Router, after the ToastProvider
- The Analytics component will now track page views and user interactions across all routes

### 3. Added ESLint Configuration
**Created:** `.eslintrc.cjs`
- Added ESLint configuration file to enable code linting
- Configured for React 18.2 with modern JavaScript (ES2020)
- Included recommended ESLint rules and React-specific plugins

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was placed inside the `<Router>` component but outside the `<MainLayout>` and `<ToastProvider>` components. This placement ensures:
- The tracking script loads once for the entire application
- Route changes are automatically tracked by the Vercel Analytics system
- Analytics data is collected without interfering with the app's UI structure

## Testing

✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
✅ No new linting errors introduced by the Analytics integration
✅ Package installed and dependencies resolved correctly

## Next Steps

To enable analytics on Vercel:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Navigate to the project in the Vercel dashboard
3. Click the "Analytics" tab
4. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics
5. After the next deployment, analytics will be active at `/_vercel/insights/*`

## Notes

- The Analytics component works seamlessly with React Router for automatic route tracking
- No additional configuration is required; analytics will work in production by default
- The implementation follows Vercel's official guide for React applications
